================================================================
==== beat-4
================================================================
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
 BEAT 4 — ADOPT  (the human-gated agent lifecycle)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
 TALKING POINT:
   This is the flagship. conduit takes the accepted decision's STORED plan —
   no AI at runtime — and posts it as an issue on the client's own forge.
   Then it stops. Three human gates, by name: nothing runs until a reviewer
   labels the issue conduit:run (the scope gate); every change arrives as a
   pull request under the client's own review tooling (the review gate); and
   only a human can merge — conduit has no merge method, the gate is
   unrepresentable in its type system (the merge gate). You never have to
   trust an agent; you review a pull request, which your team already knows
   how to do. And when it's merged, we don't claim success — we machine-
   verify it: six contract checks against the live forge.

 RUN: conduit plan 5   (stored plan -> forge issue; NO AI environment)
   plan for ADR-0005: stored plan (deterministic read from the ADR document)
   conduit: auto-creating missing label "adr:ADR-0005" (neutral grey) — add it to ensure_labels if this is a standing label
   planned ADR-0005 as task adr-0005 — issue 1 on gitea como/playbook at http://localhost:3000: label it conduit:run to start

 RUN: the reviewer labels the issue conduit:run   (the SCOPE gate — in real life: the forge UI)
bash demo/demo-trigger.sh
   labeled issue 1 with conduit:run (as reviewer)

 RUN: conduit run --once   (one tick: Scoped -> Coding -> InReview)
   conduit run: single tick via gitea como/playbook at http://localhost:3000 (engine: fake (complete))

